trans-unit.source: Usage
trans-unit.target: Usage

trans-unit.source: For individuals
trans-unit.target: For individuals

trans-unit.source: Any individual developer can use Visual Studio Community to create their own free or paid apps.
trans-unit.target: Any individual developer can use Visual Studio Community to create their own free or paid apps.

trans-unit.source: For organizations
trans-unit.target: For organizations

trans-unit.source: An unlimited number of users within an organization can use Visual Studio Community for the following scenarios: in a classroom learning environment, for academic research, or for contributing to open source projects.
trans-unit.target: An unlimited number of users within an organization can use Visual Studio Community for the following scenarios: in a classroom learning environment, for academic research, or for contributing to open source projects.

trans-unit.source: For all other usage scenarios:
trans-unit.target: For all other usage scenarios:

trans-unit.source: In non-enterprise organizations, up to five users can use Visual Studio Community.
trans-unit.target: In non-enterprise organizations, up to five users can use Visual Studio Community.

trans-unit.source: In enterprise organizations (meaning those with >250 PCs or >$1 Million US Dollars in annual revenue), no use is permitted beyond the open source, academic research, and classroom learning environment scenarios described above.
trans-unit.target: In enterprise organizations (meaning those with >250 PCs or >$1 Million US Dollars in annual revenue), no use is permitted beyond the open source, academic research, and classroom learning environment scenarios described above.

trans-unit.source: For more information, see the Visual Studio Community license terms.
trans-unit.target: For more information, see the Visual Studio Community license terms.
